      {
        name: 'The Ghost of Christmas Past',
        description:
          'The Ghost of Christmas Past is the first spirit to visit Scrooge and the catalyst for his emotional awakening. Its appearance is deliberately paradoxical — simultaneously old and young, with a bright light emanating from its head and a great extinguisher cap under its arm. This visual contradiction reflects the nature of memory itself: the past is both distant and immediate, dim and illuminating. The light symbolises truth and self-knowledge, while the extinguisher cap represents the human desire to suppress uncomfortable memories — a desire Scrooge eventually acts on when he forces the cap onto the Ghost\'s head, trying to extinguish the painful truths it reveals. The Ghost speaks gently and leads Scrooge through pivotal memories: his lonely childhood, his time with Fezziwig, and his loss of Belle. Each memory peels back a layer of Scrooge\'s defensive miserliness, revealing the emotional wounds beneath. Dickens structures these visions carefully, moving from isolation to joy to loss, creating an emotional trajectory that mirrors the stages of grief. For WJEC candidates, this spirit demonstrates Dickens\'s understanding that change begins with self-awareness — Scrooge cannot reform until he understands how and why he went wrong.',
        keyQuotes: [
          {
            quote: 'These are but shadows of the things that have been. They have no consciousness of us.',
            analysis:
              'The Ghost\'s reassurance that the visions are "shadows" establishes the nature of the supernatural experience — Scrooge is an observer of his own past, unable to interact with or change it. The word "shadows" suggests both insubstantiality and darkness, implying that memories are both fragile and potentially troubling. That the figures "have no consciousness of us" creates a one-way emotional connection: Scrooge can feel, but cannot be felt, heightening his sense of loss and isolation from his former self.'
          }
        ]
      }
