        description:
          'Hyde is Jekyll\'s dark alter ego, the physical embodiment of his suppressed evil. He is consistently described in terms of deformity, smallness, and animalism, yet no character can precisely identify what makes him so repulsive. Enfield describes "something wrong with his appearance; something displeasing, something downright detestable." This inability to articulate Hyde\'s wrongness is central to Stevenson\'s technique: Hyde represents an evil that is felt instinctively rather than rationally understood. Physically, Hyde is smaller and younger than Jekyll — "pale and dwarfish" — reflecting the idea that the evil side has been "less exercised" and is therefore less developed. Yet his strength is disproportionate: he tramples a child without hesitation and beats Carew to death with extraordinary violence. Hyde\'s physical appearance may also reflect Victorian physiognomic theories, which held that moral character was visible in physical features, and degeneration theory, which feared that humanity could regress to a more primitive state. Hyde has no conscience, no empathy, and no capacity for self-restraint. He is pure appetite and aggression. Stevenson gives him very little dialogue, keeping him opaque and mysterious — more force of nature than fully realised character. For WJEC analysis, Hyde should be discussed as a symbol of the repressed Victorian id, the dangerous consequences of suppressing natural impulses, and the era\'s anxieties about evolutionary regression.',
