        description:
          'Utterson is the novella\'s primary narrator and viewpoint character — a lawyer whose restrained, rational temperament embodies the values of Victorian professional masculinity. He is described as "lean, long, dusty, dreary" and "yet somehow lovable," a man who suppresses his own pleasures (he drinks gin to "mortify a taste for vintages") and maintains strict self-discipline. Utterson\'s function in the narrative is twofold: he is the detective figure whose investigations drive the plot, and he is the embodiment of the Victorian values of discretion, loyalty, and respectability that the novella both portrays and critiques. Utterson\'s loyalty to Jekyll is tested throughout the text, and his instinct is always to protect his friend\'s reputation rather than expose the truth. This discretion, while admirable in one sense, also enables Jekyll\'s destructive behaviour to continue unchecked. Utterson repeatedly encounters evidence of Hyde\'s evil but rationalises it away or defers confrontation, suggesting that Victorian propriety can become complicity with wrongdoing. His limited perspective also shapes the reader\'s experience: because we see events through Utterson\'s baffled, cautious viewpoint, the truth about Jekyll and Hyde is withheld until the final chapters, creating the novella\'s characteristic suspense. For WJEC candidates, Utterson represents the Victorian gentleman\'s code of conduct — honourable but limited, well-meaning but ultimately inadequate in the face of the primal forces the novella unleashes.',
